                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.41/106.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Page</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-22">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 22, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Sir Edward Grey showed me a telegram he is sending to Spring Rice asking United
                    States Government’s permission for a British Consul to investigate Benton’s
                    death. He thinks such an investigation, in addition to our own or in conjunction
                    with it, will quiet excitement here. House of Commons summoned him to-day out of
                    regular order to question him. He informed me that he wished the truth to be got
                    at independently of Villa’s version, and he expressed confidence in our good
                    will and in the effectiveness of our investigation if we take it vigorously in
                    hand and summons all possible witnesses.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
